<Bent="Bent: First attempt at distorting a photo into a landscape of sorts. Never really amounted to much tho I kinda like the lonely mountain in what might be the foreground."/>
<BentCity="BentCity: The bent cityscape. Walking in Baltimore and feeling depressed by one boring townhouse after another, I started wondering what the city would be like if it were a little less dirty brick and a little less rectangular That led me to take a photo and distort it to imagine the result."/>
<Brush3c="Brush3c: A supernova of ideas with unconscious shapes in the background reacting to the explosion of shape in the foreground. It started out overwhelmingly reddish but I keep diddling with it changing color and composition to make it less flat."/>
<Doodle="Doodle: Started out a a simple iphone doodle that got better then worse and it never managed to make it into what I wanted but different enough from my other paintings that I have reconciled myself to whatever it is."/>
<Doodle2="Doodle2: A very early iphone doodle left pretty much in its original shape and form. Does not try to do too much and I like it despite the simplicity."/>
<Doodle3="Doodle3: Another early iphone doodle made with a plan to use a lot of yellow. Finger paint and see what happens. Inspired by the Noonday Raga painting of Laxman Pai, which it looks nothing like, aside from the preponderance of yellow."/>
<Doodle6e="Doodle6e: Based on a simple iphone doodle. I printed up an earlier version of this after I had crapped up simple w/too much useless stuff. The current version rubbed out much of that and added better shading. It looks good small. Not so sure about big."/>
<Doodle7="Doodle7: What is shown here is a cropped version of a larger painting, which is interesting but the cropped version works in that it is focused more on the girl who gets lost in the larger painting."/>
<Doodle9="Doodle9: An abstract landscape inspired by the maple trees that grow around ponds in New England and which turn bright red in early autumn. When I went to get this printed on canvas and they brought it out, a cute girl waiting in line behind me said that is so cool. Totally made my day and that is what I think of when I look at it to this day and it pretty much also determines how I feel about it."/>
<Doodle10a="Doodle10a: Intended to be a play on texture avoiding the way too busy trap I tend to step into. I think it would look good on a big canvas but have been hesitant to find out."/>
<Doodle11="Doodle11: From my way too busy period (which goes on and on). I look at it as a tropical man digging in his garden with his daughter looking on. Admittedly, that is an abstact interpretation."/>
<Doodle12b="Doodle12b: A cropped and colorized version of a larger canvas that I feel I never got right."/>
<Doodle13="Doodle13: This lacks a foreground and even tho it has been sitting around a long time, I consider it unfinished. In my head what it is becoming is coming into focus but not got there yet."/>
<Doodle14="Doodle14: I did this thinking of Rusky, my father and while it is in no way a portrait, for some reason it reminds me of him."/>
<Fractal2="Fractal2: Gods on a date. One of a number of very busy paintings that started from a fractal image. Patterns out of control. I never figured out how to make do more with less."/>
<Fractal2a="Fractal2a: The first of a series of paintings based on the same fractal image. As with many of my paintings, this one is busy, probably way too busy but that is what I was working on at the time. I wanted to end up with something to examine."/>
<Fractal2c="Fractat2c: A lone flower in an imaginary garden. Trying for a cosmic feel but pooched that with too much happening to no purpose."/>
<Fractal3="Fractal3: The bitter pill that attempts to offset too much doodling with a simple shape in the foreground. It looks nice against a red wall. I find the key to any painting is finding a good place to display it and since many of my paintings are color riots, the background colors of thier resting place is important."/>
<LatticeB="LatticeB: This is a colorized and revised version of an early painting that no one liked, not even me. In my head this does not quite get there but maybe if I let it sit longer and get back to it ..."/>
<Lego2a="Lego2a: A hot mess playing with shapes and patterns that make no attempt to depict anything but carve out a space on the digital canvas. Never had it printed but have been tempted to wondering how it would look on a yellow wall. Originally considered this abject failure but it grows on me as long as I do not look at it often."/>
<Lego5="Lego5: It started out as a Mandelbrot image but I colored all over it. One of my few attempts to paint something not overly encrusted with color and pattern. I consider it a simple exercise that came out better than expected."/>
<Lego6="Lego6: An imaginary landscape at daybreak. Nothing too realstic."/>
<Merge2a="Merge2a: A lot of effort went into this. It started out as a phone doodle by my brother Gregg onto which I inflicted my penchant for adding complexity. The structure of the original doodle holds it together and the complexity is blended in. I often wonder what it would look like on a big canvas."/>
<Nataraja="Nataraja: The Lord of the dance. Feeling a little different at the time, I decided to paint something to capture whatever that feeling was. This is a nataraja, Siva dancing. I have often thought of doing a sequel but not got around to it. No problem with lack of foreground here."/>
<NoWayJose="NoWayJose: Based on a distorted photo taken outside the No Way Jose bar in Federal Hill in Baltimore. There is no way to recognize the original photo in it. Like many of my paintings, it suffers from a lack of foreground but I like the composition."/>
<Stairs="Stairs: Done around the same time as NoWayJose, this is based on a photo of stairs in my Baltimore townhouse, distorted into a landscape of slightly warped reality. Stairs on acid."/>
<Star="Star: This started out when I was showing granddotter Paige how I did my digital painting. I was into painting colorful worm like things."/>
<Swirl="Swirl: Aptly named in that there are a lot of swirly things happening that I like, however, the composition does not do it for me. Another painting that could use a new and improved sequel."/>
<Wash="Wash: Laxman Pai, the Indian painter from Goa who was a family friend did a green raga that my father Rusky had but he sold it or gave it away. I set out to do a big green painting to replace it and this is what resulted."/>
